setoptions(thickness=2): #set the thickness of the lines in the plots</Text-field></Input></Group><Section collapsed="true"><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1"><Font family="Times New Roman">Introduction</Font></Text-field></Title><Group><Input><Text-field layout="_pstyle259" style="_pstyle259"><Font family="Times New Roman">I show how to use Fourier series to compute approximations of function on a finite interval. I discuss the ease of use of <Font style="_cstyle268">odd and even continuations</Font>. This leads to <Font style="_cstyle269">Fourier Sine or Cosine series</Font>.</Font></Text-field></Input></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 1" style="Heading 1"><Font family="Times New Roman">Section 1: Even vs Odd expansions </Font></Text-field></Title><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">Consider the triangle:</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">g:=x*(Heaviside(x)-Heaviside(x-1))+(2-x)*(Heaviside(x-1)-Heaviside(x-2));</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot(g,x=0..2,title="The triangle");</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">f1:=x;f2:=(2-x);</Text-field></Input></Group><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2"><Font family="Times New Roman">Even expansions</Font></Text-field></Title><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">ge:=x*(Heaviside(x)-Heaviside(x-1))+(2-x)*(Heaviside(x-1)-Heaviside(x-2))+(-x)*(Heaviside(x+1)-Heaviside(x))+(2+x)*(Heaviside(x+2)-Heaviside(x+1));</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot(ge,x=-2.01..2.01);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">The coefficient </Font><Equation input-equation="a[0]" style="2D Comment">NiMmJSJhRzYjIiIh</Equation></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">a[0]:=1/4*Int('f',x=-2..2)=2*(1/4*(int(f1,x=0..1)+int(f2,x=1..2)));</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">The coefficients </Font><Equation input-equation="a[n];" style="2D Comment">NiMmJSJhRzYjJSJuRw==</Equation></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">a[n]:=2*1/2*Int('f'*cos(n*Pi/2*x),x=-2..2)=simplify(2*1/2*(int(f1*cos(n*Pi/2*x),x=0..1)+int(f2*cos(n*Pi/2*x),x=1..2)));</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">The coefficient  </Font><Equation input-equation="b[n]" style="2D Comment">NiMmJSJiRzYjJSJuRw==</Equation><Font family="Times New Roman"> are all zero </Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">A[k]:=subs(n=k,simplify(2*1/2*(int(f1*cos(n*Pi/2*x),x=0..1)+int(f2*cos(n*Pi/2*x),x=1..2))));</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">Let call S(n,x), the Fourier series approximations with n coefficients:</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">S:=(m,x)-&gt;1/2+sum(A[k]*cos(k*Pi/2*x),k=1..m);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">S(3,x);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">Now, we look at different approximations of S as m increases:</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot([ge,S(3,x),S(7,x)],x=-2..2,title="Higher approximations: n=3 (Green),n=7 (Blue)",color=[red,green,blue],numpoints=100);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">The approximation gets better., Let's try some higher order approximations</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot([S(100,x)],x=-6..6,title="Higher approximations: n=100 (Blue)",color=[red,blue],numpoints=150);</Text-field></Input></Group></Section><Section><Title><Text-field layout="Heading 2" style="Heading 2"><Font family="Times New Roman">Odd expansions</Font></Text-field></Title><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">go:=x*(Heaviside(x)-Heaviside(x-1))+(2-x)*(Heaviside(x-1)-Heaviside(x-2))+(x)*(Heaviside(x+1)-Heaviside(x))+(-2-x)*(Heaviside(x+2)-Heaviside(x+1));</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot(go,x=-2.01..2.01);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">The coefficients   </Font><Equation input-equation="a[n];" style="2D Comment">NiMmJSJhRzYjJSJuRw==</Equation><Font family="Times New Roman"> are all zero (including n=0) </Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">b[n]:=2*1/2*Int('f'*sin(n*Pi/2*x),x=-2..2)=simplify(2*1/2*(int(f1*sin(n*Pi/2*x),x=0..1)+int(f2*sin(n*Pi/2*x),x=1..2)));</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">The coefficient  </Font><Equation input-equation="b[n]" style="2D Comment">NiMmJSJiRzYjJSJuRw==</Equation><Font family="Times New Roman"> are all zero </Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">B[k]:=subs(n=k,simplify(2*1/2*(int(f1*sin(n*Pi/2*x),x=0..1)+int(f2*sin(n*Pi/2*x),x=1..2))));</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">Let call S(n,x), the Fourier series approximations with n coefficients:</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">S:=(m,x)-&gt;sum(B[k]*sin(k*Pi/2*x),k=1..m);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">Now, we look at different approximations of S as m increases:</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot([go,S(3,x),S(7,x)],x=-2..2,title="Higher approximations: n=3 (Green),n=7 (Blue)",color=[red,green,blue],numpoints=100);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">The approximation gets better., Let's try some higher order approximations</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot([S(100,x)],x=-6..6,title="Higher approximations: n=100 (Blue)",color=[red,blue],numpoints=150);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" style="Normal"><Font family="Times New Roman">Comparison between odd and even expansions</Font></Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">Seven:=(m,x)-&gt;1/2+sum(A[k]*cos(k*Pi/2*x),k=1..m);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input">plot([S(j,1),Seven(j,1)],j=2..51,title="Convergence of the even expansion (blue) and odd expansion (red) at one point x=1",color=[red,blue],numpoints=50);</Text-field></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"/></Input></Group><Group><Input><Text-field layout="Normal" prompt="&gt; " style="Maple Input"/></Input></Group></Section></Section><Section 